close_symbols: const char (the pointee type of FunctionName)
explanation: UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs: Need the function prototype and implementation to confirm how the parameters passed from UT_DefaultStubImpl are used. In particular, verify that the callee does not get the addresses of UT_DefaultStubImpl's parameter variables (e.g. via &FunctionName or &FuncKey) by macro/inline expansion, and to ensure no macro-based expansion alters the caller's parameter objects. va_start (macro), va_end (macro), va_list (type): These stdarg symbols are used in UT_DefaultStubImpl. The va_start macro can reference the address/stack slot of the last fixed parameter (DefaultRc) on some ABIs; we must inspect the actual macro/ABI behavior to be sure va_start/va_end do not modify the parameter variable itself or create aliasing that would constitute modification of a parameter object. UT_EntryKey_t (type/typedef) and int32 (type/typedef): Determine whether these are plain scalar types or typedefs to pointer or more complex types. If a parameter type is actually a pointer typedef, the analysis must distinguish between modifying the pointer variable (prohibited) and modifying the object pointed-to (allowed). const char (the pointee type of FunctionName): Confirm the const qualification on the FunctionName parameter (pointer to const char) to ensure the function is not permitted to modify the pointed-to characters; also verify whether any hidden typedef/macro changes that qualification. Together these symbols provide the type/prototype and macro context needed to determine if UT_DefaultStubImpl itself modifies any of its parameter variables (which would violate the MISRA rule).
